  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Psychologic status is associated with poor outcome after joint arthroplasty and perhaps
      chronic pain. To enhance the therapeutic effect of a psychologic intervention, the specific
      disorders or pain-related beliefs that contributed to chronic pain should be identified. We
      therefore determined whether specific psychologic disorders (depression, anxiety disorder) or
      health-related beliefs (self-efficacy, pain catastrophizing) are associated with chronic pain
      after joint arthroplasty for osteoarthritis.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
